John Edward: Language skills are essential for global citizens
Scotland’s independent schools have many great academic achievements behind them, and it remains in 2018 with yet another series of outstanding exam results, which are further enhanced by individual and collective success in sports, art, music and other efforts in the local environment.
With up to 30,000 students around Scotland, these schools, represented by The Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the best level of service to their students and parents.
The independent schools try to prepare their students for further and higher education, their chosen career and their place as global citizens.
As an education sector that can compile and implement a tailor-made curriculum, we find that modern languages remain a popular topic in schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you talk to a man in a language he understands, he hits that head.
If you talk to him in his own language, it hits the heart.”
It’s an important reminder that we can’t just stick to English when we want to build relationships and trust among people from other countries.
We can look at the latest exam results this year, that languages are highest in the statistics with the most passed exams in the independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of the students who studied foreign languages received the high grade A.
The data collected by SCIS' 74 member schools showed that 72 percent of students received grade A in Mandarin, while 72 percent of those who studied German, 69 percent of those who studied French, and 63 percent of those who studied Spanish also received an A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as important skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Language is now perceived as subject choice at the same level as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in independent schools’ pensa and elsewhere.
A 2014 survey by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills found that, among the reasons employers could not fill vacancies, 17% had to do with language skills shortages.
Therefore, language skills are becoming more and more important in preparing young people for their future careers.
More job opportunities will require language skills in the future, and these skills are essential in a globalised world.
Whatever career the young people choose, if they have learned another language, they have a great advantage in the future with a lifelong skill like this.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically gives a multilingual person a head start for competitors.
According to a YouGov poll of over 4,000 respondents in the UK in 2013, 75 percent could not speak a foreign language well enough to conduct a conversation, and French is the only language spoken by a multi-digit percentage, 15 percent.
Therefore, it is important to invest in language teaching for those who are children today.
Speaking multiple languages, especially languages from developing countries, gives children a better chance of finding meaningful work.
In Scotland, there is a difference between schools and the languages in which they are taught.
A number of schools focus on the more classical modern languages, while others teach languages that are expected to be most important to the UK when looking forward to 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child is interested in, there will always be a variety of languages to choose from at independent schools with teachers who are specialists in the field.
Scottish independent schools are dedicated to providing a learning environment that prepares children and gives them the skills required to succeed, no matter what the future holds.
At the moment, it cannot be denied that languages continue to be really important for the country's future in a global business environment, and this must be reflected in the training programmes.
Modern languages should really be considered "international communication skills".
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, this diversity and this award to Scotland’s youth.
It has to be done.
John Edward is the President of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
