Students at Harvard take a course on getting enough sleep
A new course at Harvard University has given all undergraduate students more sleep. The purpose of the course is to counteract the growing macho culture where studying all night long kept up with large amounts of caffeine.
One researcher has shown that students at the world’s best university often don’t know the first thing about taking care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at the Brigham and Women's Hospital, has made the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He got the idea for the course after giving a talk about the effects of sleep deprivation on learning.
"When the essay was finished, a girl came up to me and said, 'Why do I get to know this now when I'm on the candidate?'
“She said no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, which is offered for the first time this year, explains to students how good sleeping habits can improve one’s academic and sporting performance as well as one’s overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health field, says the university has decided to offer the course after finding out that the students were in severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The one-hour course consists of various interactive exercises.
In one of the exercises, there is a picture of a college room where students have to click on coffee cups, curtains, running shoes and books to gain knowledge about the effects of caffeine and light, and how one’s athletic performance is affected by sleep deprivation, and how important good sleep habits are.
In another part of the course, participants hear about how sleep deprivation over a long period of time increases the risk of heart attacks, blood clots, depression and cancer.
Participants are encouraged to think about their daily habits by clicking on different icons on an interactive map of campus.
"We know that it will not change the behavior of students immediately.
But we think they have a right to know – just like you have a right to know how cigarettes affect health,” adds Professor Czeisler.
The pride in taking an "allnighter" still exists, he says, adding that modern technology and increased pressure on the students has led to sleep deprivation being a growing problem.
The “secret weapon” against stress, exhaustion and anxiety is good and adequate sleep, he said – it even counteracts weight gain because lack of sleep makes the brain think you’re hungry, why they’re constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studies chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler organize the course last year when he took one of his courses on his first year at Harvard.
