Algae bloom update: Concentrations reduced in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows that there is a general decreasing algae concentration in parts of Tampa Bay.
According to the FWC, widespread flowering is reported in the area around Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier – suggesting that the concentration is decreasing.
The blooming of algae spreads over a coastline of 210 km from northern Pinellas County to southern Lee County.
There are fewer blooms about 16 km from the coast in Hillsborough County, but there are fewer than last week.
There have also been outbreaks in Pasco County.
Medium concentrations have been reported in or at sea in Pinellas County during the last week, low to high concentrations in the ocean outside Hillsborough County, background concentration to high concentrations in Manatee County, background concentration to high concentrations in or in the ocean outside Sarasota County, background concentration to medium concentrations in Charlotte County, and background concentration to medium concentrations in the ocean outside of Charlotte County.
Respiratory distress continues to be reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
No respiratory problems have been reported in northwestern Florida in the past week.
